'''''Kahaani''''' ({{IPA-hns|<U+02C8>k ha<U+02D0>a<U+02D0> <U+0273>i<U+02D0>|IPA}}; {{lang-en|''Story''}}) is a 2012 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller film]] directed, co-written and co-produced by [[Sujoy Ghosh]]. The film features [[Vidya Balan]], [[Parambrata Chatterjee]] and [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]] in lead roles. Balan portrays the role of Vidya Bagchi, a pregnant woman in search of her missing husband in the city of [[Kolkata]] during the [[Durga Puja]] festivities, who is helped in her quest by Satyaki "Rana" Sinha (Chatterjee) and Khan (Siddiqui).

Made on a shoestring budget of {{INRConvert|8|c}}, ''Kahaani'' was developed by writer Advaita Kala, based on the initial idea from Ghosh. The film explores themes of [[feminism]] and [[motherhood]] in a predominantly male-dominated [[Socio-economic issues in India|Indian society]]. Filming took place on the streets of Kolkata with Ghosh employing the art of [[guerrilla filmmaking]] to avoid unwanted attention. Ghosh admitted to using several allusions to [[Satyajit Ray]]'s films such as ''[[Charulata]]'' (1964) and ''[[Aranyer Dinratri]]'' (1970). Additionally, critics compared the [[twist ending]] of the plot to the Hollywood film ''[[Taking Lives (film)|Taking Lives]]'' (2004). The film was noted for a deft portrayal of Kolkata and use of a significant number of crew and cast members from the city.

''Kahaani'' released worldwide on 9 March 2012 to major critical acclaim with praise directed to the screenplay, the cinematography and the performances of the lead actors. Word of mouth publicity and good critical response paved the way for ''Kahaani'' to emerge as a major commercial success at the box office, with a 50 day worldwide gross of {{INRConvert|104|c}}. The film resulted in renewed interest in Kolkata as a filming location, and the character of contract killer Bob Biswas became an [[internet phenomenon]] in India.

== Plot ==
The film opens with a poison-gas attack on a [[Kolkata Metro|Kolkata Metro Rail]] compartment, killing the passengers on board. Two years after the incident, a [[London]]-based pregnant [[software engineer]] Vidya Bagchi (Vidya Balan) arrives in [[Kolkata]] around [[Durga Puja]] festivities in search of her missing husband, Arnab Bagchi. A police officer Satyaki "Rana" Sinha (Parambrata Chatterjee) offers her help. Although Vidya claims that Arnab came on an assignment for the National Data Center (NDC), initial probes suggest that no person named Arnab was working in NDC.

Agnes D'mello, HR head at NDC, suggests to Vidya that her husband resembled Milan Damji (Indraneil Sengupta), an ex-employee of NDC. Before Agnes could obtain Damji's records, she is killed by Bob Biswas (Saswata Chatterjee), an assassin working undercover as a life insurance agent. Vidya and Rana break into the old office of NDC to collect documents on Damji. They barely manage to escape a close brush with Bob, also looking for the documents. Meanwhile, the attempts to obtain Damji's records rattle two [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] (IB) officials<U+2014>the IB chief K. Bhaskaran (Dhritiman Chatterjee) and his deputy Khan (Nawazuddin Siddiqui). Khan arrives in Kolkata and reveals that Damji was an IB agent gone rogue and was responsible for the poison-gas attack. In spite of warnings by Khan, Vidya continues her relentless search, fearing that Arnab's resemblance to Damji has led him into trouble.

The residential address on Damji's record leads Vidya and Rana to a dilapidated flat. An errand boy of the neighbourhood tea stall, Poltu, informs them that the resident of that flat occasionally had a visitor. Poltu identifies R. Sridhar, an officer of NDC, as the person who had visited Damji's flat. This leads Sridhar to instruct Bob to kill Vidya. Following a failed attempt to kill Vidya, Bob is run over by a [[Tempo (car)|tempo]] during a chase. Examination of Bob's mobile phone leads Vidya and Rana to an IP address sending instructions to kill her. They break into Sridhar's office to verify his IP address but Sridhar gets alerted electronically, and returns to his office pursuing the duo. Following a scuffle, Vidya shoots Sridhar accidentally which upsets Khan as he wanted Sridhar alive.

Khan reveals that Rana had been working for him all along, using Vidya as a tool. Although not happy at being used as a ploy, Vidya agrees to help Khan on his request but ignores Rana. Sridhar's computer data reveals a code which is deciphered to be Bhaskaran's phone number. Vidya calls Bhaskaran to tell him that she has retrieved sensitive documents from Sridhar's office and if Bhaskaran helps Vidya find her husband, she would hand over the documents to him. Bhaskaran tells Vidya to contact the local police as he is not associated with this. However, Vidya soon gets a call from an unknown number, warning her that she should hand over the documents to the caller if she wishes to see her husband alive. Khan thinks the caller is Milan Damji.

As instructed, Vidya goes to meet Damji, with Rana and Khan in pursuit. During their negotiations about the documents and the whereabouts of her husband, Damji attacks Vidya hitting her in the abdomen. He points his gun at Vidya to kill her, but is thwarted by the prosthetic abdomen which Vidya has been using to fake her pregnancy. She kills a baffled Damji and flees in the crowd before the arrival of police, leaving a thank you note for Rana and a pen drive containing data from Sridhar's computer. Rana, based on several past incidences, deduces that no Vidya or Arnab Bagchi ever existed. It is she who has been using the police and IB for her motive. The data from the drive leads to Bhaskaran's arrest. Vidya is revealed as the widow of Arup Basu (Abir Chatterjee), an IB officer and a colleague of Damji, who was killed in the poison-gas attack. In her mission to take revenge of her husband's death, Vidya was helped by retired IB officer Colonel Bajpai (Darshan Jariwala), who suspected the involvement of some top IB officials in the attack.

== Cast ==

* [[Vidya Balan]] as Vidya Venkatesan Bagchi, a seven month pregnant woman who travels from London to Kolkata to search for her missing husband, Arnab Bagchi.
* [[Parambrata Chatterjee]] as Satyaki "Rana" Sinha, a rookie cop who helps Vidya Bagchi in her quest to learn the truth about her missing husband.
* [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]] as Khan, the deputy of the Intelligence Bureau of India, an arrogant man with a no-nonsense attitude.
* [[Indraneil Sengupta]] as Milan Damji, a terrorist responsible for a poison-gas attack on the Kolkata Metro Rail.
* [[Dhritiman Chatterjee]] as Bhaskaran K., the head of the Intelligence Bureau of India.
* [[Saswata Chatterjee]] as Bob Biswas, a contract killer who doubles as a life insurance agent.
* [[Darshan Jariwala]] as Colonel Pratap Bajpai, a retired officer of the Intelligence Bureau of India.
* [[Abir Chatterjee]] as Arup Basu, a member of the Intelligence Bureau, who tries to prevent Damji's attack on the Metro Rail but eventually gets killed.
* Shantilal Mukherjee as R. Shridhar, a corrupt NDC official
* Kharaj Mukherjee as Inspector Chatterjee, a friendly inspector at the Kalighat Police Station.
* Colleen Blanche as Agnes D'mello, the human resources head of NDC who is murdered in the process of helping Vidya
* Nitya Ganguli as Mr. Das, the guest house owner
* Ritabrata Mukherjee as Bishnu, a worker at the guest house
* Pamela Bhuttoria as Sapna, an employee at NDC
* Kalyan Chatterjee as Paresh Pal, a clay artist and a police informer
* Ridhi Sen as Poltu, a worker at a tea-stall

== Production ==
=== Development ===

[[Sujoy Ghosh]] approached novelist and script-writer Advaita Kala with a nascent idea of the film.<ref name=Kala@ZN>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan is the hero of 'Kahaani', says scriptwriter Advaita Kala|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-balan-is-the-hero-of-kahaani-says-scriptwriter-advaita-kala_75637.htm|accessdate=30 March 2012|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=16 November 2010|agency=[[Press Trust of India]] (PTI)}}</ref> The initial proposed name of the film was ''Kistimaat'' (meaning checkmate).<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> Kala developed the story resembling a memoir on the city of Kolkata, where she had followed the footsteps of her boyfriend in 1999, quite akin to the protagonist in the film.<ref name="mitra toi 3-16">{{cite news|last=Mitra|first=Ipshita|title=Vidya's journey was my own: Advaita Kala|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-16/books/31142700_1_kahaani-sujoy-ghosh-vidya-balan|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=16 March 2012|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> She reported that despite facing a language barrier and the chaos and poverty of the metropolis, she was bowled over by the warmth of the people of the city, which was reflected in the film.<ref name="real life znews"/> Kala started writing the story in 2009 and finished it up by February 2010, the effort culminating in a 185-page work.<ref name="dasgupta toi 1152012">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-15/news-interviews/30627829_1_novel-sujoy-ghosh-release|title=Vidya's Kahaani to release as novel|last=Dasgupta|first=Priyanka|date=15 January 2012|accessdate=26 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=[[Times News Network]] (TNN)}}</ref> She stated, "It was challenging to write the script as I had to do a lot of research on the subject. I went back to Kolkata, refreshed elements, went back to my own experiences to get the real picture of the city which is shown in the movie."<ref>{{cite web|title=Kahaani: Advaita Kala says she had to tell Vidya's story right|url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/advaita-kala-had-to-tell-vidyas-story-right/237060-40-103.html|last=Bhardwaj|first=Malvika|publisher=[[IBN Live]]|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref> Kala's research included reading the books ''Open Secrets: India's Intelligence Unveiled'' by Maloy Krishna Dhar and ''India's External Intelligence: Secrets of [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW)'' by V.K. Singh.<ref name="mitra toi 3-16"/> As of March 2012, Kala, whose maiden novel ''Almost Single'' was a trend-setter in India's [[chick lit]] genre,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://india.nydailynews.com/article/8b94bbe330889778462ad2a15e3d16b7/bollywood-must-treat-women-as-heroes-kahaani-writer-advaita-kala|title=Bollywood must treat women as heroes: 'Kahaani' writer Advaita Kala|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)]]|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|Indo Asian News Service]] (IANS)|date=26 April 2012|accessdate=8 may 2012|last=Chattrejee|first=Madhusree}}</ref> planned to publish the story of the film in the form of a novel later in that year.<ref name="real life znews">{{cite news|title='Kahaani' story inspired from real-life experiences|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/kahaani-story-inspired-from-real-life-experiences_107223.htm|publisher=Zee News|accessdate=21 March 2012|date=7 March 2012|agency=PTI}}</ref>

{{quote box|width=33em|align=right|quote="For me, the reason behind shooting in Kolkata was that the world in the film has to look believable. As a writer, I have to know my city<U+2014>the darkness and the light of the city. I know Kolkata and I wanted to exploit it to the peak in terms of characterization."<ref name=Ghosh@ZN />|source=<U+2014>Sujoy Ghosh on choosing Kolkata}}
Ghosh began to work on the screenplay of the film while he was waiting for the release of his previous film ''[[Aladin (2009 film)|Aladin]]'' (2009), but the dismal response to ''Aladin'' was a setback. He had to approach several producers to back him, but was refused<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> and discouraged from making the film owing to three major factors<U+2014>a pregnant woman as the lead star, a bunch of unknown Bengali actors as the supporting cast and Kolkata as a backdrop.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Kahaani'' everything that a film should not be: Sujoy Ghosh|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/kahaani-everything-that-a-film-should-not-be-sujoy-ghosh_109182.htm|accessdate=10 April 2012|publisher=Zee News|date=9 April 2012|agency=PTI}}</ref> He finally resumed work in 2010, on the insistence of Balan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/sep/080910-informer-4.htm|title=Finally Sujoy Ghosh's Kahani to go on floor|date=8 September 2010|newspaper=[[Mid Day]]|accessdate=19 March 2012|author=The Hitlist Team}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2012/kahaani-child-of-vidya-balan-sujoy-ghosh-060312.html|title=Kahaani is a child of Vidya Balan: Sujoy Ghosh|date=6 March 2012|work=Oneindia.in|accessdate=19 Mar 2012}}</ref> According to the director, [[Yashraj Films]] nearly agreed to produce the film. However, Ghosh was asked to sign an agreement to direct three films which he eventually declined.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

The idea of setting the film in Kolkata came from Bengali film actor [[Prosenjit Chatterjee]], who insisted upon Ghosh to shoot in the city.<ref name="KahaaniOfKahaani">{{cite news|url= http://expressbuzz.com/entertainment/news/the-story-behind-kahaani/366382.html|title=The story behind 'Kahaani'|first=Ayaz|last=Shaikh|date=26 February 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> Ghosh finalized Kolkata as the background due to several reasons including the director's acquaintance with the city, the mix of modernity and old world charm that the city presents,<ref name="KahaaniOfKahaani"/> and the budget constraints as making cinema in Kolkata is cheaper than [[Mumbai]] or [[Delhi]], the usual shooting location of the majority of [[Bollywood]] films.<ref name="moneycontrol ghosh iv">{{cite news|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/entertainment/if-kahaani-failed-id-have-to-pack-my-baggo-sujoy-ghosh_689018.html|title=If Kahaani failed I'd have to pack my bag & go: Sujoy Ghosh|publisher=Moneycontrol|date=4 Aprl 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012|agency=CNBC-TV18}}</ref>

In an interview with [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-IBN]], Ghosh admitted that with his two preceding directorial ventures ''[[Aladin (2009 film)|Aladin]]'' and ''[[Home Delivery (film)|Home Delivery]]'' performing miserably at the box ofiice, ''Kahaani'' was his last chance to create a niche.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview flop">{{cite video|people =Ghosh, Sujoy|year =2012|month= March
|title =Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on Kahaani|url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related
|type=Television production|time=1:25|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate =30 March 2012 }}</ref> He further added that the twist at the end of the plot came somewhat accidentally. He related the skeleton of the story to one of his friends in Kolkata during the development of the story. That friend called him back a few days later, and just asked him about how his film was going. The friend mistakenly imagined some sequences which he assumed to be parts of the plot. Ghosh got the idea of the twist from these assumed sections of the plot.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview twist">{{cite video|people =Ghosh, Sujoy|year =2012|month= March
|title =Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on Kahaani|url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related
|type=Television production|time=4:10|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate =30 March 2012 }}</ref>

=== Casting ===

Vidya Balan was the first choice of both writer Advaita Kala and director Sujoy Ghosh to play the protagonist in ''Kahaani''.<ref name="real life znews"/> Ghosh planned to work with Balan since long and approached her even before Balan's 2010 film ''[[Ishqiya]]'' was released.<ref name=Ghosh@ZN>{{cite news|title='Aladdin' flopped as I failed to tell a story: Sujoy Ghosh|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/aladdin-flopped-as-i-failed-to-tell-a-story-sujoy-ghosh_105652.htm|agency=IANS|publisher=Zee News|accessdate=6 April 2012|date=10 February 2012}}</ref> When Ghosh narrated her the brief initial outline of the plot, Balan turned the offer down. After several rejections, she finally agreed to do the film when she read the completed script.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya played choosy before saying yes for 'Kahaani'|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-played-choosy-before-saying-yes-for-kahaani_105993.htm|publisher=Zee News|agency=IANS|accessdate=21 March 2012|date=16 February 2012}}</ref> On his fascination to cast Balan, Ghosh said, "The good thing about performers like Vidya is that when you give them something, they take it with them and bring something of their own. For me, having Vidya was a boon because she did so many things herself. What she has brought to her character is completely her own. She's a really chilled out actress any director can ask for."<ref name="KahaaniOfKahaani"/>

Apart from Balan, Ghosh chose a host of Bengali actors as he wanted to make the characters look and sound as real as possible.<ref name="Sujoy on toes @ HT">{{cite news|last=Ghosh|first=Debasmita|title=I wanted to be on my toes: Sujoy Ghosh|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/I-wanted-to-be-on-my-toes-Sujoy-Ghosh/Article1-822989.aspx|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=9 March 2012}}</ref> He said, "For me, having actors who look like the characters they play is half the job done. When [''sic''] they can act well or not comes next."<ref name="inside Story @ Hindu">{{cite news|last=Dundoo|first=Sangeetha|title=The inside story|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3006073.ece|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=17 March 2012}}</ref> The role of the Inspector Satyaki "Rana" Sinha was first offered to [[Chandan Roy Sanyal]] but he couldn't fit that into his schedule due to other commitments.<ref name="Team Tolly @ TT" /> So Parambrata Chatterjee, an actor of [[Bengali language|Bengali]] cinema, was chosen to play the role. Ghosh met Chatterjee in 2006 when the latter was showcasing his film ''[[The Bong Connection]]'' at the [[Mumbai Academy of the Moving Image]] festival. Impressed by Chatterjee's work in the film, Ghosh offered him the role in ''Kahaani''.<ref name=Parambrata@Rediff>{{cite web|title=Meet the other hero of Kahaani|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-parambrata-chatterjee/20120316.htm|publisher=[[Rediff]]|date=16 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012|first=Patcy|last=N}}</ref> Chatterjee had earlier worked with Balan in the [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali film]] ''[[Bhalo Theko]]'' (2003), which was Balan's film debut.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-23/news-interviews/31229680_1_vidya-balan-sujoy-ghosh-film-kahaani|title=Vidya Balan my best co-star: Parambrata Chatterjee|date=23 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=26 March 2012|agency=PTI}}</ref>

The casting director Roshmi Banerjee suggested Nawazuddin Siddiqui for the role of Khan. Siddiqui, who was doing only minor roles in Bollywood at that time, was surprised that for the first time he got a character where he would not have to portray a beggar.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> Saswata Chatterjee, another Bengali actor, was surprised as well when he was offered the role of the contract killer Bob Biswas. He thought there were competent actors in Hindi film industry suitable for the role.<ref name="pheno 3 ibn">{{cite news|url=
http://ibnlive.in.com/news/politicians-beware-bob-biswas-says-ek-minute/245154-8-66.html|title=Bob Biswas: Saswata Chatterjee, the man behind the cult assassin|last=Chatterjee|first=Rituparna|date=3 April 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|publisher=IBN Live}}</ref> He claimed that Ghosh knew him since childhood and impressed with his acting, so he wanted only him as Bob Biswas.<ref name="toi 30march12chatterjee">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Kahaani-is-my-huge-break-Saswata-Chatterjee/articleshow/12455053.cms|title=Kahaani is my huge break: Saswata Chatterjee|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=TNN|date=30 March 2012|accessdate=30 March 2012|author=[[Times News Network]]}}</ref>

Ghosh went against the expectations of casting a popular actor from Bollywood and signed on [[Abir Chatterjee]], an actor of Bengali film industry, to play the role of Balan's husband. According to him, popular Bollywood actors were not willing to work with him after the debacle of his two previous films. He also believed that a known face would have been a disadvantage because there would be popular expectations about increased screen-time for a known actor. He said, "My film is a thriller but the husband is seen in the earliest part of the film by the audience. A known star would have been a spoiler." <ref name="Sujoy @ India West">{{cite web|first=Vijayakar|title=Sujoy Ghosh: 'Kahaani' Could Be the Story of Any Mother|url=http://indiawest.com/news/3597-sujoy-ghosh-kahaani-could-be-the-story-of-any-mother.html|publisher=India West|accessdate=22 May 2012|date=19 March 2012}}</ref> Several other Bengali film and television actors such as Indraneil Sengupta and Kharaj Mukherjee were cast in supporting roles in the film.<ref name="Team Tolly @ TT">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120316/jsp/entertainment/story_15255285.jsp|title=The Kahaani of Team Tolly|date=16 March 2012|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>

=== Characters ===
Several characters were thought about in minute detail. Before the shooting of the film began, Balan started flaunting a baby bump to look as close to authentically pregnant as possible for her role. According to news reports, she met doctors and pregnant women to learn about the typical lifestyle and nuances of a pregnant woman, along with making a list of dos and don'ts of pregnancy. The actor made a list of superstitions followed by pregnant women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan gets into character of pregnant woman for 'Kahaani'|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-balan-gets-into-character-of-pregnant-woman-for-kahaani_104909.htm|accessdate=26 March 2012|publisher=Zee News|date=30 January 2012|agency=[[Asian News International]] (ANI)}}</ref> Balan said that during her college days, she often used to imitate pregnant ladies during stand up acting among friends.<ref name="cakewalk">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-11/news-interviews/30615282_1_sujoy-ghosh-kahaani-pregnant-woman|title=Playing pregnant woman was cakewalk for Vidya Balan|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=IANS|date=11 January 2012|accessdate=9 May 2012|last=Chaubey|first=Abhishek}}</ref> That experience helped her during the shooting.<ref name="cakewalk"/>

Ghosh, while briefing the character of the contract killer Bob Biswas to the actor Saswata Chatterjee, used the phrase ''"Binito Bob"'' (meaning polite Bob), which crystallized the notion of Bob. Further discussions led to the inclusion of paunch and a bald patch. Saswata devised the mannerism of rubbing his nails together as some Indians believe doing that helps prevent hair fall. The mannerism was well-noted and praised by the viewers.<ref name="toi 30march12chatterjee"/> Ghosh expressed his gratitude to Chatterjee for portraying Bob Biswas in an effective manner. He emphasized that the character of Bob Biswas is akin to a common man, and Chatterjee portrayed it in a way that the viewers can expect Bob to be around them anytime and anywhere.<ref name="Pop art on Saswata # TOI">{{cite news|last=Mukherjee|first=Roshni|title=Pop art on Saswata Chatterjee's character|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-22/news-interviews/31224239_1_sujoy-ghosh-fan-frenzy-character|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Times of India|date=22 March 2012|agency=TNN}}</ref>

On the character of Rana, Parambrata mentioned, "Rana does not come from an affluent strata of society while I have a very educated and urban background. He has a rural upbringing. For the role, I had to visit some police stations and do some research on their work, mindset and other relevant things. I also got a lot of help from Sujoy and Vidya. Both knew what they were doing and I just followed their vision."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/im-not-thinking-of-future-in-bollywood-parambrata-chatterjee/927457/0|title=I'm not thinking of a future in Bollywood: Parambrata Chatterjee|last=Nivas|first= Namita|date=23 March 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>

The character Khan was envisaged as a ruthless expletive spewing officer who cares nothing about the emotional or social consequences of his behavior.<ref name="ghosh starananda interview khan">{{cite video|people =Ghosh, Sujoy|year =2012|month= March
|title =Sujoy Ghosh, director of Kahani, exclusive interview with Star Ananda|url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtNMKGLGbCU
|type=Television production|language=Bengali|time=8:15|publisher=Star Ananda|accessdate =30 March 2012}}</ref> On his character, Siddiqui commented, "I was shocked when Sujoy offered me the role. How was I supposed to bring out so much of arrogance? But Sujoy had the conviction that I would be able to pull it off. Today, I feel glad when people address me by my screen name Khan because they've almost identified me with the role I've played."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Nawazuddin-Siddiqui-on-a-roll/articleshow/12273536.cms|title=Nawazuddin Siddiqui on a roll|last=Dasgupta|first= Priyanka|date=15 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=TNN|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> Ghosh built Khan as a character with lean physical built, and full of mental strength, loyalty and patriotism.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> Khan uses a particular relatively cheap brand of cigarette despite his high official post. Even in real life, Siddiqui had smoked that brand of cigarette throughout his struggling days in Bollywood and thereafter.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

=== Filming ===
Filming took place on the streets of Kolkata with Ghosh often employing the art of [[guerrilla filmmaking]] (shooting in real locations without any previous knowledge of onlookers) to avoid unwanted attention.<ref name="GhoshInterview">{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan is a character driven actress: Sujoy Ghosh|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-11/news-interviews/31145194_1_kahaani-sujoy-ghosh-aladin|accessdate=11 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=TNN|date=15 March 2012}}</ref> Ghosh chose a completely new team to work with, barring the music composers [[Vishal-Shekhar]] as he thought the presence of a fresh crew would always keep him on his toes. He thought people who he knew too well from before might influence him to overlook mistakes in film making.<ref name="Sujoy on Toes @ HT">{{cite news|last=Ghosh|first=Debasmita|title=I wanted to be on my toes: Sujoy Ghosh|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/I-wanted-to-be-on-my-toes-Sujoy-Ghosh/Article1-822989.aspx|accessdate=6 June 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=9 March 2012}}</ref> The film was shot continuously in a schedule of 64 days<ref name="Cakewalk @ ZN">{{cite news|title=Playing pregnant woman was cakewalk for Vidya|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/playing-pregnant-woman-was-cakewalk-for-vidya_103659.htm|accessdate=21 May 2012|publisher=Zee News|date=11 Jan 2012|agency=IANS}}</ref> including the [[Durga Puja]] festival days of 2010 in Kolkata. The climax, which takes place on the night of [[Vijayadashami]] (last day of Durga Puja), was actually shot on the night of Vijayadashami in the premises of a ''[[Barowari]]'' (publicly organized) Durga Puja celebration in the [[Ballygunge]] neighborhood of Kolkata. Most of the crowd in the climax were non-actors. Some actors mingled with the crowd<U+2014>their job was to appreciate the camera angles and accordingly apply ''[[sindoor]]'' (vermilion) on Balan's face so that accidental exposure of her eyes to ''sindoor'' could be avoided.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh">{{cite web|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/archive/1120407/7enter.html|title=Kahini|trans_title=Story|last=Ghosh|first=Sujoy|date=7 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012|work=Anandabazar Patrika|language=Bengali}}</ref> The director admitted that one challenge was to deal with the people who did not have any inkling about the on-going shooting, and often stared straight at the camera or the characters.<ref name="yahoo march 2 2012">{{cite web|url=http://my.entertainment.yahoo.com/news/sujoy-ghosh-saves-vidya-balans-life-while-filming-183000812.html|title=Sujoy Ghosh saves Vidya Balan's life while filming 'Kahaani'|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=26 March 2012|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|author=Movie Talkies}}</ref> The sequences in [[Kolkata Metro]] were shot in a span of 4 days.<ref name="ndtv metro">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?ID=ENTEN20120196145&keyword=bollywood&subcatg=MOVIESINDIA&nid=183539|title=Kolkata Metro clears Vidya's scene in Kahaani|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=9 May 2012|publisher=[[NDTV]]}}</ref>

The guest house where the protagonist stayed in the film was chosen by Ghosh, who happened to see the three-storied building through the window of a neighboring hotel on an evening in April 2010. The place was later booked for a schedule of 10 days for {{INRConvert|40|k}}.<ref name="StarChamber" /> Ghosh chose a room with windows overlooking a busy road and gave the place an old-fashioned look by replacing the designer grills of the window in the room with old-fashioned wooden ones, and by painting the room with some rough patches. The guest house employees were requested to keep the shooting schedule a secret.<ref name="StarChamber" />

=== Themes ===

According to [[Zee News]], ''Kahaani'' is a [[woman's film]] about "role reversals, breaking of stereotypes, turning clich<U+00E9>s inside out, a woman's journey, and the way she carves a niche for herself in the male-dominated mentalscape of the society."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-s-kahaani-has-a-male-heroine_107445.htm|title=Vidya's 'Kahaani' has a 'male' heroine!|publisher=Zee News|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref> Trisha Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' refers to Vidya's journey through the streets of Kolkata as "a collective dream<U+2014>the unvoiced dream all women have, in which the city might belong to us as much as it does to men."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/she-belongs-to-the-city/925371/0|title=She belongs to the city|newspaper=Indian Express|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=30 March 2012|first=Trisha|last=Gupta}}</ref> In addition, Ghosh states that one aspect of his project, "is a study of motherhood" which he views as a transformation that women experience from a "petite little girl to the most powerful individual there who will go to any extent to protect her baby even if that includes slapping a physically powerful man if he is messing around. So, it is the protective instinct that draws her out and also something that drove me to write this story."<ref name=Sujoy@Rediff>{{cite web|last=Pathak|first=Ankur|title=There are two heroes in Kahaani: Vidya Balan and Kolkata|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-sujoy-ghosh-vidya-balan-is-the-hero-of-my-film/20120306.htm|publisher=Rediff|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> Some critics suggest that women's films are now more popular after ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' which won Balan her first [[National Film Award for Best Actress]],<ref name=NFA@Rediff>{{cite web|title=Vidya Balan bags National Award for The Dirty Picture|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/vidya-balan-bags-national-award-for-the-dirty-picture/20120307.htm|accessdate=16 March 2012|publisher=Rediff|date=7 March 2012}}</ref> was well received,<ref>{{cite news|last=S|first= Arpana|title=Bollywood woman power: Vidya, Ekta carry the baton|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Bollywood-woman-power-Vidya-Ekta-carry-the-baton/Article1-780176.aspx|newspaper=Hindustan Times|agency=IANS|accessdate=13 December 2011|date=9 December 2011}}</ref> and had a strong box-office response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3790&nCat=|title=Ladies Vs Ricky Bahl mixed opening The Dirty Picture super hit|publisher=BoxofficeIndia.com|date=10 December 2011|accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> The symbolism of goddess [[Durga]] was utilized in the film, by comparing the protagonist's killing of the villain with the allegorical yearly return of goddess Durga to slay the demon.<ref name="mukherjee TT 4-12-12">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120412/jsp/opinion/story_15361368.jsp#.T6lsl9kqxJF|title=A tale of two cities|last=Mukherjee|first=Uddalak|date=12 April 2012|accessdate=8 May 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>

A theme that recurred a few times in the film is the fleeting hint of romance between the cop Rana and the protagonist Vidya. Ghosh said in one interview that the delicate romance between these two characters was "the most progressive thing" he did in the film<U+2014>suggesting a boy falling in love with a pregnant woman. The director explained that the boy was initially "fascinated by someone who is literally a hero in his eyes," as Rana was awed by the computer skills of Vidya. Gradually, the fascinated boy moves into a zone where he tries to protect her. Ghosh said that this was his design, but could be performed on screen only because of the outstanding performance of the two actors involved.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview romance">{{cite video
|people =Ghosh, Sujoy|year =2012|month= March|title =Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on Kahaani
|url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related|type=Television production|time=2:07|publisher=IBNLive
|accessdate =30 March 2012 }}</ref>

