[[Pratim D. Gupta]] of ''[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]'' rated the film 9 out of 10, calling it a "a mind-juggling medley of manipulation masquerading as a 'mother of a story'".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gupta|first=Pratim D.|title=What a kahaani|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120310/jsp/entertainment/story_15231247.jsp#.T3F0dEoQgrU|accessdate=27 March 2012}}{{Rating|9|10}}</ref> [[Taran Adarsh]] of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave the film 4 out of 5 stars, saying, "Post ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'', the admiration for the National Award winning actress Vidya has scaled woozy altitudes and let me affirm, the supremely talented actress delivers a performance that's at par with her former accomplishments."<ref>{{cite web|last=Adarsh|first=Taran|title=Kahaani|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/542221|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=8 March 2012}}{{Rating|4|5}}</ref> Madhureeta Mukherjee of ''[[The Times of India]]'' rated the film 4 out of 5 stars, commenting, "Once again, a 'pregnant' Vidya, ironically displays more 'male ornaments' (excuse the watering down) than most heroes." The rating was later revised to 4.5 stars out of 5, owing to popular feedback.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kahaani|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/hindi/Kahaani/movie-review/12188039.cms|accessdate=8 March 2012|newspaper=The Times Of India|date=8 March 2012|first=Madhureeta|last=Mukherjee}}{{Rating|4.5|5}}</ref> Sukanya Verma from [[Rediff]] awarded the film 4 out of 5 stars, stating, "Vidya Balan excels in ''Kahaani'', a film which is much too enjoyable to find flaws."<ref name="rediff Review">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-vidya-balan-rocks-in-kahaani/20120309.htm|title=Review: Vidya Balan rocks in Kahaani|first=Sukanya|last=Verma|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=9 March 2012}}{{Rating|4|5}}</ref> Subhash K. Jha for [[Indo-Asian News Service|Indo Asian News Service]] gave the film 4 stars out of 5, saying, "''Kahaani'' is one of those rare films that can easily lay claim to being a game-changer."<ref>{{cite news|last=Jha|first=Subhash K.|title=Review: Kahaani|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_review.aspx?id=689|accessdate=5 April 2012|publisher=NDTV|agency=IANS|date=9 March 2012}}{{Rating|4|5}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-IBN]] rated the film 3.5 out of 5 stars, saying, "It's a delicious thriller."<ref>{{cite news|last=Masand|first=Rajeev|title=Masand: A taut 'Kahaani' is a delicious thriller|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-a-taut-kahaani-is-a-delicious-thriller/237674-47-84.html|accessdate=5 April 2012|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|date=10 March 2012}}{{Rating|3.5|5}}</ref> Shomini Sen from [[Zee News]] rated the film 4 out of 5 stars, stating, "Watch the film purely for the story. Watch it for the beautiful Kolkata which comes alive on screen. And yes Vidya is an added bonus."<ref name="ZeeNews">{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/review-vidya-kolkata-in-a-never-seen-before-avatar-in-kahaani_107278.htm|title=Review: Vidya, Kolkata in a never-seen-before avatar in 'Kahaani'|last=Sen|first=Shomini|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=10 March 2012|publisher=Zee News}}{{Rating|4|5}}</ref> [[Anupama Chopra]] of ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' stated that, "''Kahaani'' is a nifty thriller with an enjoyment quotient that is indirectly proportionate to how long you spend thinking about the plot."<ref name="choprahindustan">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Anupama-Chopra-s-review-Kahaani/Article1-823366.aspx|title=Anupama Chopra's review: Kahaani|last=Chopra|first=Anupama|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=17 March 2012|work=Hindustan Times}}{{Rating|3.5|5}}</ref> ''[[The Hindu]]'' stated, "Worth every rupee paid to watch the movie. Not to be missed."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/nxg/article2994454.ece|title=Kahaani<U+2014>twists in the tale|work=The Hindu|accessdate=14 March 2012|first=Balaji|last=Ravi}}</ref> Noted film actress and multiple [[National Film Awards|National Award]] winner, [[Shabana Azmi]] lauded Balan for her performance and said, "I had to watch ''Kahaani'' because of Vidya. I was bowled over by her performance. As an actor, I could see she was making all the right moves throughout the film. There was not a single artificial note in her performance."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-should-avoid-pitfall-of-doing-central-parts-shabana_107995.htm|title=Vidya should avoid pitfall of doing central parts: Shabana|publisher=Zee News|agency=IANS|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>

However, a number of reviewers criticized the climax and certain features of the film, feeling that they deviated from the general style of the film. Rituparna Chatterjee of CNN IBN noted that the climax of the film was a "huge dampener" and explained, "The diabolic twist at that juncture got underplayed by capitulating to what is crassly referred to as what the Indian audiences demand from a Hindi film. What follows is a sobfest, a repeat of a candle light vigil scene from Balan's earlier film ''No One Killed Jessica'' and the apologetic explanation of why she does what she does. Justifying her action comes across more as an effort to appease the Indian morality..."<ref name="chatterjeeibn3122012">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/kahaani-why-the-film-doesnt-work-for-me/238393-8-66.html|title=Kahaani: why the film doesn't work for me|last=Chatterjee|first=Rituparna|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=15 March 2012|publisher=CNN-IBN}}</ref> The ''[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook]]'' review noted, "At times, ''Kahaani'' is too clever, at others extremely pedestrian like in the depiction of computer hacking and IB operations, not to speak of the ludicrous terrorist angle and the all-too predictable Durga Puja setting for that mythology tie-in." It adds that, "The ending feels more clumsy than menacing as Ghosh begins to explain each detail at length<U+2014>very literally. The spoon-feeding takes the intrigue away."<ref name="joshioutlook">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?280230|title=Movie review: Kahaani|last=Joshi|first=Namrata|date=26 March 2012|accessdate=17 March 2012|work=[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook]]}}{{Rating|3|5}}</ref> Gautaman Bhaskaran in his review in ''[[Gulf Times]]'' noted that the sometimes handheld photography was "...as irksome as the plot with a sleuth too many and cops galore. Often, they place snags not signs on the viewer's vision. At the end of the film, some links seemed to lead nowhere or not quite well-explained<U+2014>a habit with some helmers who feel that this is the way to sound and seem intelligent."<ref name="gautaman gt 14-3-12">{{cite news|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/mritems/streams/2012/3/14/2_492652_1_255.pdf|format=PDF|title=The story of ''Kahaani''|last=Bhaskaran|first=Gautaman|newspaper=Gulf Times|page=6|date=14 March 2012|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>

=== Box office ===
[[File:Vidya Balan at success bash of 'Kahaani'.jpg|thumb|right|230 px|Balan and Parambrata Chatterjee (r-l) celebrating the success of ''Kahaani''.]]

Though the film received critical acclaim, it was a slow starter at the box office, opening to a poor response on the first day<ref name="BO1">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4138&nCat=|title=Weekend Expectation|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia.Com|accessdate= 10 March 2012|date=10 March 2012}}</ref><ref name="BO2">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=4129&nCat=|title=Kahaani to overtake Chaar Din Ki Chandni|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia.com|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=10 March 2012}}</ref> but gradually picking up by the end of its first week of theatrical run. On its opening day, the film collected {{INRConvert|2.60|c}} of which {{INRConvert|75|l}} came from paid previews. The bulk of the business came from the five circuits of Mumbai, Delhi-Uttar Pradesh, Punjab, West Bengal and Mysore, giving a contribution of over 80%.<ref name="BO2" /><ref name="BO3">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4171&nCat=|title=Kahaani is super hit: heads for 45<U+2013>50 crore|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia.Com|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> However, the film picked up on Saturday collecting {{INRConvert|4.75|c}} and Sunday collecting {{INRConvert|5.25|c}}, resulting in a {{INRConvert|13.83|c}}<ref name="BO bullseye @ TT" /> nett in its first weekend. The film managed to fetch close to {{INRConvert|2|c}} from the state of West Bengal alone within the first three days of its release. At multiplexes in Kolkata, box office revenues raised from 47% on Friday to 77% on Saturday and to around 97% on Sunday.<ref name="BO bullseye @ TT">{{cite news|title='Bidya' hits BO bullseye&nbsp;<U+2014> Calcutta's Kahaani is a word-of-mouth rage|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120313/jsp/calcutta/story_15241893.jsp|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=13 March 2012|first=Priyanka|last=Roy}}</ref>

The film collected nearly {{INRConvert|24|c}} in the first week, well past its production cost of {{INRConvert|8|c}}.<ref name="konarutv">{{cite web|url=http://www.yourmoneysite.com/news/2012/mar/vidya-balans-kahaani-rakes-nearly-rs-24-cr-from-box-office-in-week-one.html|title=Vidya Balan's Kahaani rakes nearly Rs 24&nbsp;cr from box-office in week one|last=Konar|first=Arundhati|publisher=Bloomberg UTV|date=17 March 2012|accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> By the third week, the film grossed {{INRConvert|75|c}} including India and overseas market.<ref name="75crore@IBN">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/kahaani-grosses-rs-75-crore-at-the-box-office/242076-8-66.html|title=Kahaani grosses Rs 75 crore at the box office: the story behind the numbers|publisher=CNN-IBN|accessdate= 23 March 2012|date=23 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kahaani-whats-the-story-behind-the-numbers-253056.html|title=Kahaani overall gross|publisher=Firstpost|accessdate=22 March 2012|author=FirstPost staff|date=22 March 2012}}</ref> ''BoxOfficeIndia'' declared the film a "Super Hit" after the second week of its theatrical run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4192&nCat=|title=Agent Vinod average opening Kahaani extraordinary week two|publisher= Boxofficeindia.Com|accessdate= 24 March 2012|date=24 March 2012}}</ref> ''Kahaani'' was successful in the international box office as well, garnering {{INRConvert|8|c}} within 10 days of its release in seven markets<U+2014>UK, US, UAE, Australia, New Zealand, Malaysia and Pakistan.<ref name="adarsh overseas 20-3">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/trade/boxofficeoverseas/id/412|title='Kahaani' overtakes 'TDP' in overseas|last=Adarsh|first=Taran|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> The film made a worldwide gross of {{INRConvert|104|c}}<ref name="ht 50 gross"/> within 50 days of its release.

== Visuals and motifs ==
=== Portrayal of Kolkata ===
[[File:Traffic in Kolkata.jpg|thumb|left|A road in Kolkata showing congested traffic and yellow taxis]]
Some reviewers noted that a major protagonist in the film is the city of [[Kolkata]] itself, commenting that the director portrayed Kolkata as "brimming with warm, sympathetic inhabitants",<ref name="rediff Review"/> offering a multitude of glimpses of everyday life of the city.<ref name="rediff Review"/> As one review mentioned, "Ghosh pays a fond yet understated tribute to the city's essence and elements<U+2014>yellow taxis, leisurely trams, congested traffic, claustrophobic metros, dilapidated brick houses, tapering alleys, ''[[Polianthes tuberosa|rajnigandhas]]'', ''lal paad saris'', piping hot ''[[luchi]]s'' and a gorgeous depiction of how the city acquires a whole new level of luminosity and ''shakti'' during the famed [[Durga Puja]]." It was also noted that the film did not bank on the usual stereotypes of Kolkata culture often used in Bollywood films, such as "O-emphasizing accent, dramatic play of conch shells, ''[[rasgulla]]''/''[[mishti doi]]'' excesses."<ref name="rediff Review"/>

The visual portrayal of the city was praised by a critic, who stated, "Dark, lingering, soulful, amusing, festive, enigmatic and unchanging<U+2014>Kolkata is multiple people in a city's body. This varied, pulsating and intriguing temperament is what is documented in its yellow-toned frames without distracting itself from the story or its telling."<ref name="rediff Review"/> The director admitted, "For me, Kolkata wasn't supposed to be an object. Kolkata is a person and had an emotional index. When Parambrata drives down Vidya to the guest house for the first time, I deliberately show how the evening is slowly setting in. That's how my Kolkata enters every frame and finally becomes a central character of my film."<ref name="dasguptatoi152012">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Kahaani-takes-Kolkata-beyond-cliches/articleshow/12273109.cms|title='Kahaani' takes Kolkata beyond cliches|last=Dasgupta|first=Priyanka|newspaper=The Times of India|agency=TNN|date=15 March 2012|accessdate= 15 March 2012}}</ref>

However, certain cinematic experts argued that the portrayal of Kolkata in ''Kahaani'' was "cosmetic", akin to a [[Lonely Planet]] exotica,<ref name="gautaman gt 14-3-12"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-24/news-interviews/31233578_1_srijit-mukherji-films-shooting/3|title=Hemlock is far from a morbid film: Srijit Mukherji|newspaper=The Times of India|last=Ojha|first=Satadru|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> and that it lacked a warranted, deep menacing presence.<ref name="mukherjee TT 4-12-12"/> The experts further said that the film was sometime s lacked subtlety, and that the depiction of the city never matched the level of [[Satyajit Ray]]'s [[Calcutta trilogy]]<U+2014>where "...aided by bloodshed, greed and decadence, ...Calcutta..., even though a place of dreams, desires and hope, slides irreversibly into chaos, anxiety and a moral crisis, taking its residents with it.".<ref name="mukherjee TT 4-12-12"/>

=== Allusions and inspirations ===
[[File:Pratima Visarjan by Gaganendranath Tagore.png|thumb|The colour scheme of ''Kahaani'' was inspired by the painting ''Pratima Visarjan'' by Gaganendranath Tagore.]]
Ghosh admitted to several instances of allusions to [[Satyajit Ray]]'s films. In one scene in the film, Vidya asks the manager of the guest house as to why there is no hot water in the tap although the signboard of the guest house claims "running hot water". The manager explains that the errand boy of the guest house runs to deliver hot water in a kettle whenever hot water is required, and that is why the signboard says "running hot water". Similarly, in Ray's ''[[Joy Baba Felunath]]'' (1979), an elderly gentleman asked the same question to a hotel manager, and got the same reply in a somewhat scalding manner.<ref name="anandabazreview">{{cite web|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/archive/1120317/17cine1.html|title=''Asamanya''|last=Bandyopadhyay|first=Jagari|date=17 March 2012|accessdate=18 March 2012|work=[[Anandabazar Patrika]]|language=Bengali|trans_title=Extraordinary}}</ref>

In an interview with [[Pratim D. Gupta]] of ''[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]'', Ghosh commented that the way Balan looks out and moves from window to window in the guest house room is reminiscent of ''[[Charulata]]'' (1964) where the actress [[Madhabi Mukherjee]], playing a lonely wife, enjoys glimpses of the outside world through the blinds of windows. He acknowledged the inspiration of [[Framing (visual arts)|framing]] of the visuals from ''[[Mahanagar]]'' (1963), another film directed by Ray noted for its portrayal of Kolkata. According to the director, he was inspired by particular scenes of Ray's ''[[Nayak (1966 film)|Nayak]]'' (1966) to plan the portrayal of complex emotional issues between Vidya and the police officer Rana, especially Rana's awe in the presence of Vidya. Ghosh expressed his inspiration from Ray's ''[[Aranyer Dinratri]]'' (1970) by saying, "I remember an interview of Ray's where he had said that in ''Aranyer Dinratri'' he wanted the audience to be inside the car with the four guys all the time. So the camera never leaves the car. It stuck in my head. The same thing I have done here. You are like Vidya's fellow passenger."<ref name="gupta ghosh interview tt">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120314/jsp/entertainment/story_15245793.jsp|title=Salaam namaste: Sujoy Ghosh on the whys and whats of Kahaani and on being a jedi bangali|work=The Telegraph|date=14 March 2012|accessdate=18 March 2012|last=Gupta|first=Pratim D.}}</ref>

Besides Ray's films, Ghosh also admitted inspiration from the visually striking films of 1970s and 1980s, "I remember the scene in ''[[Deewaar (1975 film)|Deewaar]]'' when [[Shashi Kapoor]] walks in, sees [[Nirupa Roy]] and takes his cap off and she breaks her bangles. Nothing more, nothing less. Just images. I have used that here. Vidya comes down the stairs and sees Param standing there... he takes his cap off... just before the morgue scene."<ref name="gupta ghosh interview tt"/> Critics have also compared the fake pregnancy twist of ''Kahaani'' with similar sequences in the 2004 psychological thriller ''[[Taking Lives (film)|Taking Lives]]''.<ref name="anandabazreview"/> The sequences towards the end of the film that explains the missing pieces of the mystery were compared with a similar technique utilized in ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'' (1995).<ref name="choprahindustan"/> The director wrote that the film was heavily influenced by the colour scheme of the ''Pratima Visarjan'', a water colour painting by [[Gaganendranath Tagore]].<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

== Impact ==
=== Kolkata ===

The city of [[Kolkata]], has become a preferred destination for filmmakers in [[Bollywood]], following the critical and commercial success of the film. Ghosh commented that, "I am overwhelmed with the kind of interest Kolkata has generated among the people in Mumbai and elsewhere. It is Kolkata and not any other city which people are talking about now."<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN>{{cite news|title='Kahaani' brings Kolkata back to limelight|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/kahaani-brings-kolkata-back-to-limelight_107407.htm|accessdate=30 March 2012|publisher=Zee News|agency=PTI|date=11 March 2012}}</ref> Several film-makers have pointed that the landscape, streets and lanes of [[Mumbai]] and [[Delhi]] were overused in the films in the last few decades, while Kolkata, on the other hand, has a different appeal with its [[metro train]]s, rickety [[tram]]s, [[Pulled rickshaw|hand-pulled rickshaws]], dingy bylanes, British era buildings and iconic structures like [[Howrah Bridge]] and [[Victoria Memorial (India)|Victoria Memorial]]. [[National Film Awards|National Film Award]] winning producer-director [[Onir]], whose film ''[[I Am (2010 film)|I am]]'' (2010) was partially shot in the city, said that the present generation of Bengali filmmakers want to shoot at Kolkata, "Since we know the city very well and have many memories attached to the place, the ideas flow in very easily while shooting in Kolkata."<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN/> Director [[Anurag Basu]], whose film ''[[Barfee]]'' was shot in Kolkata for over a month stated, "If I look from the eyes of the camera all other metros look the same but Kolkata has a unique character."<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN/> [[National Film Award for Best Actress|National Award]] winner [[Rituparna Sengupta]] commented, "From foreign locations, the films have shifted their focus to Indian culture and ''Kahaani'' is one of the examples where we saw the filmmaker looking at [[West Bengal]] for inspiration."<ref>{{cite news|title=Delighted to see filmmakers reviving Bengali culture: Rituparna|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-31/news-interviews/31266331_1_bengali-culture-hindi-film-hindi-movie|accessdate=6 April 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=31 Mar 2012|agency=IANS}}</ref>

Once considered as the hub of art, culture and literature, Kolkata lost its dominance and presence in [[Indian Cinema]] after the death of renowned city-based filmmakers [[Bimal Roy]] and [[Pramathesh Barua]].<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN /> Since shooting for a [[Hindi language|Hindi]] film was not natural in a city dominated by [[Bengali language|Bengali]], Mumbai took over as a recurrent location in most of the films due to the presence of the Hindi film industry in Mumbai. Bengali filmmakers [[Aparna Sen]] and [[Rituparno Ghosh]] had in the past made films like ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'' and the [[Amitabh Bachchan]] starrer ''[[The Last Lear]]'' where Kolkata featured prominently in the background. Two of [[Vidya Balan|Balan's]] previous films<U+2014>''[[Bhalo Theko]]'' (her cinematic debut) and ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'' (2005) (her [[Bollywood]] debut), were also primarily shot in Kolkata.<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN /> With the city's increasing cosmopolitan culture and the Victorian aura still intact in some places, film-makers believe that the city also stands to benefit from the trend, stating the example of [[Switzerland]] which became an attractive tourist destination for Indian Cinema after [[Yash Chopra]] captured the locales of the snow-capped mountains in his films.<ref name=Kolkata_Limelight@ZN />

=== Monalisa Guest House ===

Monalisa Guest House, the tourist lodge which played host to a pregnant Vidya Bagchi in the film, became a tourist spot among the local crowd.<ref>{{cite news|title=Single screen theatres resurface to tell Vidya's Kahaani|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Single-screen-theatres-resurface-to-tell-Vidya-s-Kahaani/Article1-835430.aspx|accessdate=5 April 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=4 April 2012|agency=IANS}}</ref> The place, situated on [[Sarat Bose Road]] in the [[South Kolkata|southern part of the city]], attracted hundreds of visitors since the release of the film. While around 50<U+2013>60 visitors thronged the place daily to catch a glimpse of room number 15, where Balan stayed, the lodge witnessed the maximum crowd of about 300 people on 18 March 2012. According to the management, the film's release has increased the occupancy rate of the hotel from the previous 70 percent to 90 percent and many visitors left disheartened since the room where Balan stayed remained occupied after the film's release. Room number 15 is the only "suite" in the lodge with the highest per-day tariff of {{INRConvert|2|k}} while the other rooms ranges between {{INRConvert|980}} and {{INRConvert|1650}} per day. The management further stated that contrary to the old-fashioned look in the film, the rooms in the guest house are well equipped with basic modern facilities along with a computerized registration system to keep the records of the visitors, unlike the "thick and torn register" shown in the film. They added that the "running hot water" actually referred to the water heaters installed in the rooms and does not mean a boy supplying hot water in a kettle, as depicted in the film. Banking on the high demand and also with ''Kahaani'' as the [[Unique selling proposition|USP]] for the hotel, the hotel planned to increase the per-day tariffs by renovating the rooms with modern furniture and some photographs from the film.<ref name="StarChamber">{{cite news|title=Star chamber|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/star-chamber/468894/|accessdate=26 March 2012|newspaper=Business Standard|date=25 March 2012|first=Probal|last=Basak}}</ref>

=== Internet phenomenon ===
[[File:Bob biswas cartoon.jpg|150px|thumb|A pop art on the character Bob Biswas]]
The character Bob Biswas became an [[internet phenomenon]] following the release of the film. The harmless pot-bellied contract killer became the subject of multiple jokes, one-liners and [[pop art]]s, circulated through [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]].<ref name="pheno 1 ndtv">{{cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?Section=Movies&ID=ENTEN20120198515&subcatg=MOVIESINDIA&keyword=bollywood&nid=193308|title=Kahaani's Bob Biswas a rage on FB, Twitter|date=3 April 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|publisher=NDTV|agency=PTI}}</ref> ''"Nomoshkar, Aami Bob Biswas... Ek minute?"'' (Hello, I am Bob Biswas... do you have a minute?)<U+2014>the monologue that the character repeatedly used in the film just before murdering the unsuspecting victims<U+2014>was used in different [[internet meme|meme]]s.<ref name="pheno 3 ibn"/><ref name="pheno 2 bhaskar">{{cite news|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/SCT-SOM-nomoshkar-ek-minute-best-memes-from-bob-biswass-facebook-page-3047837.html?HF-7=|title=Nomoshkar, ek minute: best memes from Bob Biswas's Facebook page|newspaper=Daily Bhaskar|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> A [[graphic novel]] based on Bob Biswas was being planned by groups of fans of the character, as of March 2012.<ref name="pheno 4 toi">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-22/news-interviews/31224239_1_sujoy-ghosh-fan-frenzy-character|title=Pop art on Saswata Chatterjee's character|newspaper=The Times of India|date=22 March 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|agency=TNN|last=Mukherjee|first=Roshni}}</ref> A TV serial based on the life of Bob is also being planned, as of April 2012.<ref name="pheno 5 toi">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/bengali/news-interviews/Bob-Biswas-now-on-TV/articleshow/12633763.cms|title=Bob Biswas now on TV|newspaper=The Times of India|date=12 April 2012|accessdate=12 April 2012|agency=TNN|last=Jha|first=Subhash K.}}</ref>

== Sequel and remakes ==

At a special screening held for the film's cast and crew in Kolkata on 10 March 2012, Sujoy Ghosh admitted to his intentions of continuing the film as a part of an ongoing series. Ghosh was inspired by [[Satyajit Ray]]'s ''[[Feluda]]'' detective stories and desired to carry forward the stories of Vidya Bagchi on similar lines. He said, "... I knew I had stumbled on to a unique idea that I didn't want to let go of when I finished writing ''Kahaani''. What Vidya Bagchi does with her life after my ''Kahaani'', haunts me. I want to take the idea forward."<ref name="Jha franchise">{{cite news|first=Subhash K.|last= Jha|title=Kahaani to be a franchise?|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-16/news-interviews/31200857_1_sujoy-ghosh-s-kahaani-vidya-balan-franchise|accessdate=27 March 2012|newspaper= The Times of India|date=16 March 2012}}</ref> The positive critical reception and box office collection of the film strengthened the likelihood of a sequel. Ghosh further said, "''Kahaani'' was written for Balan. I can't imagine taking the character forward without her. She will have to green-light the franchise before it goes further."<ref name="Jha franchise"/>

As of May 2012, the film is set to be remade in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]]. [[Endemol#Endemol_India|Endemol India]], a TV production house, planned to venture into films with the remake of ''Kahaani'' being their first project. They bought the remake rights of the film and planned to roll the remakes on floors in September 2012 and release them in January 2013.<ref name="ibn 52012 remake">{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/tamil-remake-for-bollywood-blockbuster-kahaani/259591-71-180.html|title=Tamil remake for Bollywood blockbuster 'Kahaani'|publisher=IBN Live|date=20 May 2012|accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> On their selection of the film, Deepak Dhar, CEO, Endemol India, explained that the story had a strong emotional connect and can be adapted well for different markets.<ref name="Endemol remakes @ HT">{{cite news|last=Awaasthi|first=Kavita|title=Endemol forays into films with Kahaani remake|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Endemol-forays-into-films-with-Kahaani-remake/Article1-857675.aspx|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=18 May 2012}}</ref> Ghosh, along with reprising his role of a co-producer for the remakes, is supposed to work with a leading director from the [[South Indian film industry]].<ref name="ibn 52012 remake" />

